      <TR VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
        <TD HEIGHT=141 COLSPAN=5>
        </TD>
        <TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH=693 HEIGHT=133 COLSPAN=3>
                    
                      <div align="left">
                      <table border="0" width="696" height="136">
                        <tr><td width='686' height='19' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#ffff80> 2000-06-21 - Reverting to an Item Wipe</font> </td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='19'></td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='19' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#C0C0C0> Hello all,
<p>After a good deal of discussion on the Test server status, we have decided
that having the right or the ability to do something does not necessarily mean
that we should. Our thoughts were that everyone was aware of the risks of
playing on the Test Server, and always did so with the understanding that
something such as a character-wipe was always a possibility. Its apparent at
this point, given feedback from players on Test, that many did not understand
the risk.
<p>That said, we do need to restore the integrity of the testing environment in
order to insure that we are able to catch and address issues prior to them going
to the live servers. Test has served well in this capacity since release,
however item loot issues and other factors have reduced Tests ability to do
this. Given these issues, we still feel that a complete character-wipe
represents the best possible solution for continued functionality of the Test
server. However, this is a case where, in the interest of keeping our current
testers and players satisfied, that we need to compromise on the solution.
<p>After our discussions today, we have decided that an item-wipe, without
deleting characters, will accomplish the majority of our goal to restore the
Test server as a functional testing platform. Given that, the EQLive and
Operations teams are currently at work restoring all characters that were wiped
yesterday, with the exception of characters known to be artificially buffed.
This process should be completed later today.
<p>Furthermore, in order to allow those that did not understand the purpose or
risks associated with the Test server a chance to avoid future problems of this
nature, we will be allowing built-up (not buffed) characters a one-time chance
to move when the next split-server comes up, sometime in the near future. As
Brad mentioned in his message earlier, we do recommend that those who are on
Test more for playing, and less for Testing, seriously consider moving when we
open registration. The possibility of a future wipe, whether it is a player or
item wipe, is not necessarily unlikely in the future.
<p>We hope that the players on Test will find this compromise acceptable and
continue to participate in the testing process. Furthermore, we apologize for
the insensitivity of our previous decision to completely wipe the server.
<p>On behalf of the EverQuest team,
<p>Gordon Wrinn<br>
Internet Relations Manager<br>
Verant Interactive, Inc.<br>
</p>
</font> </td></tr><tr><td width='686' height='55' valign='top' align='left'> <font face='Arial,sans-serif' SIZE=2 COLOR=#ffff80> Source: EverQuest Message Board -  </font> <a href=http://www.pcgamer.com </a> www.pcgamer.com </td></tr>    
                      </table>
                      </div)
